data.title: Squad member Ayanna Pressley condemns decision to reinstate Boston bomber's death penalty
data.meta_description: US Rep. and Squad member Ayanna Pressley bashed the Supreme Court for its decision to reinstate the death penalty for Boston Marathon Bomber Dzhokhar Tsarnaev on Friday.
data.text:
U.S. Rep. and Squad member Ayanna Pressley slammed the Supreme Court's ruling to reinstate the surviving Boston Marathon bomber's death sentence on Friday.

In a 6-3 vote, Dzhokhar Tsarnaev, 28, was ordered back on to death row as the court agreed with the Biden administration's call to execute Tsarnaev over the April 2013 terror attack that killed three and maimed 255 others.

In a statement following the court's ruling, Pressley, a hard-left Massachusetts Democrat who represents part of Boston, said the decision was 'deeply disappointing but unsurprising for this far-right majority Court that has shown time ang again its contempt for the people.'

'State-sanctioned murder is not justice, no matter how heinous the crime,' Pressley said. 'The death penalty is a cruel and inhumane punishment that has no place in society.'

Pressley also called on fellow congress members to pass her proposed legislation to ban the death penalty and urged President Joe Biden to take executive action and halt federal executions.

'President Biden gave me his word that no one would be executed by the federal government under his watch, and I fully expect him to keep that promise,' Pressley said.

Joe Biden's attorney general, Merrick Garland, had since imposed a moratorium on federal executions, meaning Tsarnaev will languish on death row for at least the duration of Biden's presidency. The president, a Catholic, has voiced personal concerns about capital punishment in the country.

Despite his hesitations, the administration urged the Supreme Court to rule on the matter and argued that holding a new sentencing would further traumatize the Boston community by forcing victims to once again recount the horrors of that day.

No federal inmates were executed for 17 years before Donald Trump oversaw 13 executions in the last six months of his term.

Many took to social media to blast Pressley for her statement, saying it was inappropriate and hurtful to the victims of the terrorist attack and their families.

One Twitter user with handle name Aileen questioned: 'Are Pressley's constituents on board with her decision? I don't imagine they would have an issue with the death penalty for this guy.'

Mike Dreyer, another Twitter user, wrote: 'It should be up to the victims families on whether the death penalty should be implemented, not you!'

A Twitter user with the name Tricia, a fan of Pressley, said, 'Sorry - while I support you/your work, I disagree with you on this.'

Another Twitter user with the handle Jamie wrote: 'I'm sure if Ayanna Pressley had her kid or a family member blown up and killed/maimed by that terrorist she wouldn't feel bad for him and would be in favor of it.'

A Twitter user with the handle IdahoGabe also criticized Pressley's statement and questioned why life in prison would be a better sentence than the death penalty.

'I actually think it a lot crueler to keep someone locked in a cage for the rest of their life, but hey that's me,' he wrote.

The Supreme Court's ruling came as they tossed out an earlier court's ruling that jurors should have been informed of his accomplice brother's influence.

'Dzhokhar Tsarnaev committed heinous crimes,' Justice Clarence Thomas wrote for the majority, with conservatives ultimately voting to reinstate, with liberal justices coming out against. 'The Sixth Amendment nonetheless guaranteed him a fair trial before an impartial jury. He received one.'

The First U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Boston ruled in 2020 that the trial judge improperly excluded evidence that could have shown Tsarnaev was deeply influenced by his older brother, Tamerlan, and was somehow less responsible for the carnage. Tamerlan was shot dead by cops in the Boston suburb of Watertown four days after the terror attack.

The appeals court also faulted the judge for not sufficiently questioning jurors about their exposure to extensive news coverage of the bombing, but the Supreme Court has now ruled that this was a moot point.

Associate Justice Stephen Breyer, writing a dissent that was joined by two of his colleagues, noted that when 'death is at stake...particular judicial care' is required.

'In my view, the Court of Appeals acted lawfully in holding that the District Court should have allowed Dzhokhar to introduce this evidence,' Breyer wrote.

Daniel Habib, a lawyer for Tsarnaev, declined to comment about the ruling. Judy Clarke, another lawyer representing Tsarnaev, did not immediately reply to DailyMail.com's request for comment.

Tsarnaev was found guilty in 2015 for the deaths of Lingzi Lu, a 23-year-old Boston University graduate student from China; Krystle Campbell, a 29-year-old restaurant manager from Medford, Massachusetts; and 8-year-old Martin Richard, of Boston.

The attack left 255 people injured and his older brother, Tamerlan, also shot and killed MIT police officer Sean Collier. Tamerlan was killed in a shootout with the police following the bombing.

Defense lawyers had argued Tsarnaev was dominated by his violent older brother, a suspect of a 2011 triple homicide case in Waltham, Massachusetts, USA Today reported.

Tamerlan was a boxer who became radicalized in the early 2000s, sharing YouTube playlists that called for violent Islamic terrorism and allegedly pushed his younger brother to share his views and take part in the bombing.

Following the bombing, Tsarnaev had stirred controversy as he gained a rabid fandom who even sent him money while he was incarcerated.

Rolling Stone magazine received widespread backlash when it appeared to 'glamorize' Tsarnaev on its cover that made the terrorist look like a rock star, fueling his popularity.

During the trial in 2014, many of his fans, mostly women, stood outside the courthouse in Boston flashing signs and wearing shirts in support of Tsarnaev.

He and his defense had argued that the fans be removed from demonstrated outside the courthouse because they were allegedly pushing conspiracy theories that could influence the court.

In January 2022, federal judge George O'Toole order the government to swiftly seize the $1,400 COVID stimulus checks Tsarnaev received last year, as well as the money in his prison account totaling $3,885.06.

The money will go to the victims as he owes them $101 million in compensations. He has only paid about $2,200 so far.

Tsarnaev is set to remain on death row at Colorado's infamous Florence ADX supermax prison, widely regarded as the world's most secure correctional facility.
